This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing and understanding sarcasm in text. Additionally, the use of an end-to-end model and attention mechanism suggests a focus on machine learning and deep learning techniques, which are commonly used in the field of computational linguistics. 

The paper may also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the development of a model that can detect sarcasm, which is a complex task that requires a deep understanding of language and context. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category as the paper proposes an interpretable end-to-end model that combines information from multiple sources to detect sarcasm. This suggests a focus on developing machine learning models that can handle complex tasks and make use of multiple sources of information. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is also a possible sub-category as the paper considers the conversational context in detecting sarcasm, which involves analyzing social interactions and relationships between speakers. 

Finally, cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is a possible sub-category as the paper involves analyzing text to detect sarcasm, which is a task that is relevant to information retrieval and search engines.
